thread.title: Skating Club of Boston mourns 13-year-old skater, her mother and coaches
thread.title_full: Skating Club of Boston mourns 13-year-old skater, her mother and coaches

author: ERIN COOGAN, NBC 10 NEWS
title: Skating Club of Boston mourns 13-year-old skater, her mother and coaches
text: Six people -- two coaches, two athletes, and two parents -- from the Skating Club of Boston in Norwood were confirmed aboard the plane that crashed after a midair collision in Washington. \"It's really their second home,\" Skating Club of Boston CEO Doug Zeghibe told WJAR. \"Their second family. We're all feeling this.\" Among those in the crash, husband and wife figure-skating coaches Vadim Naumov and Evgenia Shishkova of Norwood. \"Everything you've heard about them, being a little tough,\" Olympic skater Nancy Kerrigan began. \"They always did it with a smile on their face. To come in here and not see that, it's going to be so weird not to see that. Especially for those who come here day in and day out.\" They were in Kansas this past week to coach some of the club's youngest elite talent at the U.S. Figure Skating National Development Camp. The couple are just two of six from the Skating Club of Boston who didn't make it home after the coveted event. Before becoming coaches at the Skating Club of Boston, the duo had claimed their own pairs title at the 1994 Figure Skating World Championships in Japan. They leave behind their son Max Naumov, who had also been in Wichita, competing in the U.S Championships, but had taken a different flight home. \"Their son is on his way to D.C.\" Zeghibe continued. \"He's scheduled to compete at the international Four Continents championship, but now I don't know if he's going to be doing that. He's also scheduled to be an alternate at the World Championships, so he has some tough decisions ahead of him and my heart goes out to him because it's both his parents.\" Meanwhile, the couple were mentors to 13-year-old Jinna Han of Mansfield, who was also on that plane with her mom. RELATED: Skaters, parents, coaches from Southern New England were on jet that crashed in Washington Of the 18 athletes sent to Kansas this past week from the Skating Club of Boston in Norwood to compete both in the U.S figure skating championships or to partake to the national development camp, Jinna was confirmed the youngest club member, killed in Wednesday night's fiery crash. \"We watched Jinna grow up here,\" Zeghibe added. \"From just a little girl into this amazingly mature 13-year-old.\" Accompanied on the trip by her mother, Jin, who staff at the Skating Club of Boston said spent just as many hours near the ice as her daughter. \"We talk a lot about the athletes, but we're seriously going to miss the parents just as much,\" Zeghibe continued. \"Just really good people.\" Club leaders described 13-year-old Jinna as not only an Olympian in the making, but also one of kindest, most driven young women you'd ever meet. \"Full of grace,\" Zeghibe concluded. \"A serious competitor, but so nice about it, and so supportive of her fellow competitors.\" \"Any time I've been able to be here, I watch these kids grow,\" Kerrigan said. \"These kids really work hard. Their parents work hard to be here. But I feel for the athletes.\" And while the grief is immense, those in the skating community say they will rebuild and return stronger than they were before.
